{
  "doc_id": "43233",
  "text": "Although increased stiffness is often associated with fibrotic muscles, [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] we recently reported that total muscle collagen content does not correlate with tissue stiffness in mdx mice. [CITATION_3] These data suggest that posttranslational modifications of collagen, such as collagen cross-linking, are critical parameters in dystrophic muscle pathology. Fibrillar collagens make up most of the collagen in skeletal muscle and are the primary load-bearing structures within the ECM. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] Fibrillar collagen a-chains form a triple helix that is secreted in a pro-form, cleaved, and cross-linked into non-reducible collagen fibrils. The mechanical strength of collagen fibrils is highly dependent on the extent of cross-link formation.",
